entry.title: Support draining the serialized data from blink::CachedMetadata
entry.content:
Currently blink::CachedMetadata is designed to hold a serialized data.

But this is a bit problematic when we just want to check the existence

of CodeCache or CompileHints in the serialized data. We want check the

existence of them on the background thread before starting a JS parser.

(See https://crrev.com/c/4956763.)



So this CL introduces a new method CachedMetadata::DrainSerializedData()

to drain the serialized data.



Also this CL adds unittests of CachedMetadata.

entry.title: Introduce CompileHintsForStreaming class
entry.content:
This CL refractors the logic which determines whether to produce or

consume the local or crowdsourced compile hint while parsing script

resources with ResourceScriptStreamer in TryStartStreamingTask() into a

new class CompileHintsForStreaming.



This logic is checking the V8CrowdsourcedCompileHintsProducer and

Consumer of the page and the cached metadata from the network service.

Currently this logic is executed on the main thread. But we are planning

to check the cached metadata on the background thread when the

background thread receives the response from the network service to

start the script parsing from the background thread.

V8CrowdsourcedCompileHintsProducer and Consumer of the page are

available only on the main thread. So we will create a

CompileHintsForStreaming::Builder object on the main thread, and call

the Builder::Build() method on the background thread.

(See https://crrev.com/c/4956763)



This CL makes V8CrowdsourcedCompileHintsConsumer::Data as

ThreadSafeRefCounted because it will be dereferenced on the background

thread.



Also this CL deletes copy constructors and assignment operators for

V8LocalCompileHintsConsumer and V8LocalCompileHintsProducer.

entry.title: Video: Change HDR10 MPO promote conditions
entry.content:
Previously, whether the HDR10 MPO should be promoted depended on

whether there's a monitor enabled system HDR feature. If so, it would be

promoted. That said, HDR10 MPO should only be enabled on HDR displays.



However, in the case of multiple monitors, if there are one SDR monitor

and one HDR monitor connected to the system simultaneously, because

we don't know which monitor enabled system HDR, the MPO will always

be enabled, and when the HDR video presented on the SDR monitor, there

will be an abnormal tone-mapping issue because of this.



Since we can't get `HWND` in `DCLayerOverlayProcessor`, to avoid

such issue, the promote condition should be restricted to:



"If any of the connected monitor doesn't support HDR or not having

system HDR enabled, then HDR10 MPO should not be promoted."



Also remove the fullscreen detection logic for HDR10 MPO, since after

we correct `kDisableVideoOverlayIfMoving` feature's behaviour, there

should be no inconsistent tone mapping result anymore.

entry.title: Fix overlapping print page indicator on overlay scrollbars.
entry.content:
In Linux and Windows, when Overlay scrollbars are enabled, the page

indicator that appears next to the scrollbars when scrolling in the

print page preview gets drawn on top of the scrollbars, instead of next

to them.



In MacOS, this issue is avoided by hardcoding a 16px margin between the

edge of the screen and the page indicator. This causes the page

page indicator to be drawn far enough to not overlap with the overlay

thumb, and to not overlap with the expanded scrollbars you see when

mousing over the scrollbars.



This CL expands this margin to also be added when Overlay scrollbars

are enabled in Windows and Linux (both regular and Fluent Overlay

scrollbars).



To reproduce this issue:

1. In Windows, enable overlay scrollbars via

chrome://flags/#fluent-overlay-scrollbars

or chrome://flags/#overlay-scrollbars

2. Go to any web page that would be printed in more than one page and

open the print preview (Ctrl+P).

3. Scroll. The floating square with the page indicator gets drawn on

top of the scrollbar's thumb, instead of floating next to it.



Tested locally in Linux and Windows with both type of scrollbars

(regular and Fluent) in overlay and non-overlay versions and verified

that everything worked as expected.

entry.title: sensors WinRT: Call OnReadingChangedCallback() via PostTask()
entry.content:
While here, also add checks to make sure each method is running on the

right sequence and make |minimum_report_interval_| guarded by |lock_|

since it is accessed by the main task runner just like |client_|.



There is a significant amount of changes in the unit tests for two

reasons:

1. We now use multiple task runners and create Reader objects in a COM

STA task runner to better simulate what happens in production.

2. Doing so has uncovered bugs in the exist tests that had to be fixed.

Namely:

- One of the biggest offenders was the use of EXPECT_CALL() with

WillRepeatedly() for expecting calls to OnReadingUpdated(). Using

only WillRepeatedly() meant the control over the cardinality of the

expectations was not very strict, and sometimes callbacks were

simply not being run.

Now that TriggerFakeSensorReading() is asynchronous and we need to

use a base::RunLoop to ensure, we are also using WillOnce() a lot

more than WillRepeatedly() so that we set one expectation, call

TriggerFakeSensorReading() and consume it immediately.

- The *Thresholding tests were affected by the problem above, and

fixing them showed that several callbacks were not being invoked.

Many checks where values were increased by the exact threshold

amount were broken because the manipulated values are floats and

doubles, and the math operations on them in the

OnReadingChangedCallback() implementations caused the comparisons

with exact values to fail. In this case, it was simpler to just

remove those specific tests, as the "values bigger than the

threshold" case are already covered by other checks.

- Also as a consequence of the above, *Thresholding tests with

multi-axis values were also broken when they went from testing that

values did not pass the threshold checks to the first test that

verifies that an axis passes the threshold check. This caused all

previous |last_sent_*| variables to be stored in the Reader, and

other calls to threshold_helper(true) would fail. The fix here was

to reorder the calls so that each axis is tested entirely before

the next.

entry.title: WebGL and PaintCanvasVideoRenderer: Don't discard color space
entry.content:
Behavior change:



When UNPACK_COLORSPACE_CONVERSION_WEBGL is BROWSER_DEFAULT_WEBGL,

this fixes uploads from HTMLVideoElement and VideoFrame to match the

WebGL spec and convert to the unpackColorSpace. If it is NONE, then

preserve the existing Chromium behavior of dropping the color space

information. This is not what the spec says to do but it is what all

other browsers do.



This will not change the behavior of using Rec709 video (far and away

the most common video color space) with an unpackColorSpace of srgb

(the default and also far and away the most common value). For other

combinations, this is likely to change behavior.



Code change:



In PaintCanvasVideoRenderer::UpdateLastImage we sometimes use the

right color space (e.g, when creating the SharedImage) and sometimes

don't (e.g, when specifying the SkImageInfo for that image), resulting

in color space information mostly being dropped on the floor.



Fix this by using the same color space information in all of

PaintCanvasVideoRenderer. Use the existing compatibility helper

function GetVideoFrameRGBColorSpacePreferringSRGB, but move it into

VideoFrame for use elsewhere.



In WebGLRenderingContextBase::TexImageHelperMediaVideoFrame, fix the

places where we would fail to specify the SkColorSpace in an

SkImageInfo. Replace unpack_color_space_is_srgb with

needs_rgb_color_conversion, because that is what is being checked.



For HTMLVideoElement and VideoFrame, if

UNPACK_COLORSPACE_CONVERSION_WEBGL is NONE then preserve the

existing behavior of dropping the color space information.

entry.title: Revert "[SurfacePolish] Fix bug about toolbar flips to white when navigating"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 2c24369515ffb61dfca8e5ae252240e41b5571e4.



Reason for revert: Toolbar color got wrong when navigate to native pages and google webpages.



Original change's description:

> [SurfacePolish] Fix bug about toolbar flips to white when navigating

> from NTP to webpage

>

> When navigating from the NTP to a webpage, the toolbar color initially

> changes to the default toolbar color during the loading phase. It will

> change to the browser tab's color or stay unchanged after the loading

> phase. The loading process occurs directly on the NTP. However, with the

> Start Surface Polish enabled, the NTP's toolbar has a different color

> than the default toolbar, and this results in a flip of white when

> navigating from NTP to webpage, as shown in the

> image:

> https://drive.google.com/file/d/1ywogmzelW1OQwGdPCvrd0EndFkAbvCoM/

> view?usp=sharing&resourcekey=0-XV6pRmumU3L4vy36HRSJ4w.

> This CL aims to fix this problem.

>

> When navigating from the NTP to a webpage, the ToolbarPhone#mVisualState

> will immediately turn from VisualState.NEW_TAB_NORMAL or

> VisualState.NEW_TAB_SEARCH_ENGINE_NO_LOGO to VisualState.NORMAL called

> by function ToolbarPhone#onTabOrModelChanged. This is the starting point

> of the loading phase.

>

> The ending point of the loading phase is the time we know if we have a

> website theme color. The time we start to know whether the website has

> its theme color is the time point ToolbarPhone#onPrimaryColorChanged()

> gets called. Since this function won't be called when the website does

> not have a specific theme color, I added a function

> ToolbarPhone#onPrimaryColorGotUpdateNotified() instead. The newly added

> function will be called at the same time if

> ToolbarPhone#onPrimaryColorChanged() gets called. And the ending point

> is marked inside this function.

>

> After this CL, the navigation process will look like

> this:

> https://drive.google.com/file/d/1FchVCPWj3DnLaMoZ1Z5Ra_7Z6SIavRSV/

entry.title: Add tests for OOPPD GDI metafile variations
entry.content:
Windows print drivers for which the browser does a PDF conversion to a

form other than regular EMF have been found to cause blank pages when

the out-of-process print drivers feature is enabled. This is due to

the Print Backend service treating all GDI jobs as one single type of

EMF object, which is problematic since PostScript is handled with a

different EMF playback method at printing time.



Gain coverage for this scenario by extending the browser tests based on

SystemAccessProcessSandboxedServicePrintBrowserTest to include the

Windows printer language type in the test parameterization.



Update the TestPrintingContext logic to support specifying the language

type that the faked printer driver is supposed to expect. This allows

for adding a check that provided page metafile data matches the

expectation.



To communicate this expected type to the Print Backend service, the

necessary additional mojom MetafileDataType must be included as part of

adding these tests. To show the current problematic behavior, the

PrintBackendServiceImpl still creates the same EMF metafile object for

this new type.



Together these changes show that the metafile objects created for

PostScript and text-only print drivers are incorrectly handled by the

Print Backend service, so that the playback of such objects will not

provide imaging as desired.

entry.title: Add PrefixedVideoFullscreen enterprise policy
entry.content:
This CL adds a PrefixedVideoFullscreenApiAvailability enterprise policy,

which controls and overrides the PrefixedVideoFullscreen RuntimeEnabled

feature.



The feature determines whether the deprecated webkit-prefixed

video-specific fullscreen APIs are available (e.g.

video.webkitEnterFullscreen()). These APIs have been deprecated since

2014, and are replaced by standard APIs (e.g.

element.requestFullscreen()).



The policy has 3 values:

- "runtime-enabled": (the default value) The API's availability is

determined by the PrefixedVideoFullscreen feature.

- "disabled": The APIs are never available.

- "enabled": The APIs are always available.



This policy is only temporary, to allow enterprises to switch to the

standard fullscreen APIs. This policy is set to be deprecated in M130,

and the APIs are set to be permanently removed thereafter.



To follow the deprecation of these APIs, see this feature:

https://chromestatus.com/feature/5111638103687168

entry.title: Rework build hacks for fuzztest+absl to be more component-build friendly.
entry.content:
absl only includes subsets of Abseil that are allowed in Chrome, while

fuzztest has additional Abseil dependencies that are not normally

allowed (e.g. flags). To work around this, fuzztest would directly

depend on these additional absl_source_set targets.



However, from a component build perspective, this is problematic,

because it is really easy to end up with multiple copies of a global in

different components. For example, the centipede binary simply would not

run in an ASAN component build unless ODR violation checks were

disabled.



The build hacks are now centralized in the `absl` and `absl_full`

target. In non-component builds, `absl_full` depends on the `absl`

target + subsets of Abseil that are banned in Chrome. However, in

component builds, `absl_full` only has the `absl` dependency: the banned

subsets of Abseil are built directly into the `absl` target.



This allows the component build to avoid random ODR violations in an

ASAN build, since the entire Abseil library is now in one component; at

the same time, the non-component build still enforces correct build

dependencies.



Note that this only addresses component build issues in Abseil itself;

it is still very easy for the component build to break in subtle ways,

e.g. if two components depend on a single source_set that defines an

Abseil flag, the flag will end up being defined in two distinct

components. At runtime, this fails, since the flag registration code

checks that multiple definitions of the flag have matching types—but

this check is based on a fake RTTI pattern that is known to be broken in

component builds (i.e. absl::Any is banned for this reason).

entry.title: CrashUploadListAndroid: Remove usage of ui::FormatBytes()
entry.content:
Otherwise, this crashes in a DCHECK in AssertSingletonAllowed().



LoadUnsuccessfulUploadList() is reached from a task started in

UploadList::Load(). That task is marked as CONTINUE_ON_SHUTDOWN (see

`kLoadingTaskTraits`).



ui::FormatBytes() eventually calls base::FormatDouble() which accesses

the singleton `g_number_format_float`. Singletons are disallowed in

CONTINUE_ON_SHUTDOWN.



To solve the crash, we keep the size as an integer and format to string

just before display in crashes.ts.



To reproduce the crash:

- Put a bad URL in MinidumpUploader.CRASH_URL_STRING

- Trigger a crash with chrome://crash (upload will be unsuccessful)

entry.title: [media] VTVD: Include conversions in decode backpressure
entry.content:
Previously, only frames being decoded by VideoToolbox contributed to

backpressure. This allowed any number of frames to be decoded while

waiting for GPU time to do the output conversion, which can result in

decoding far more frames than intended.



With this change, a decode is considered complete when VideoToolbox has

finished decoding it, the result has been converted to a VideoFrame,

and the output queue has had the opportunity to output it.

entry.title: Suppress possible double-counting of the UMA for input suppression
entry.content:
Behind a flag we already have a fix for the bug. The fix suppresses

input to the page until first paint signal arrives. Before we flip

the flag, we want to make sure that the topmost frame always receives

the signal, in order to rule out the possibility of input event starvation.



The UMA data seems to have a problem, we encountered too many

occurrences for PageLoad.Internal.SuppressedEventsTimingBeforePaint2

when max-delay is reached. This CL fixes two possible causes of the anomaly:



- If WIHM is re-used across a navigation, the max-delay timer was not

reset, and this possibly caused wrongly counting such a navigation

if it happened within 15 sec.



- We are suspecting that the `first_paint_time` received by

WIHM::RecordEventMetricsForPaintTiming maybe zero even when

max-delay is not reached. See comment#148 in the bug. To isolate

the UMA from being affected by this possibility, we are passing a

separate boolean parameter to indicate max-delay reached.



The CL also fixed uninitialized `suppressing_input_events_state_`, and renamed `WIHM::DidNavigate` to better reflect its purpose.

entry.title: [A11y] Fix regression in AXEventGenerator caused by stable ids
entry.content:
Skipping these events on nodes that are either remaining ignored,

were ignored, or are about to be ignored is a significant performance

win for the browser, and likely in ATs as well.



Ignored nodes are not exposed to ATs, and therefore firing change

events on them creates extra work without any benefit.



We were always paying this cost on some nodes, but it became worse

recently after landing stable ids CL:5328829. Previously when nodes

changed from ignored to ignored, the id often

also changed, which caused the AXNode to be a new node, and there was

no old vs new data to compare, preventing this code from running in

the first place.

entry.title: Fix wrong PLSA::ShouldScrollOnMainThread after CSS overflow change
entry.content:
This is a reland of crrev.com/c/5332198 with the following changes:

- *::MainThreadScrollingDidChange() are removed because they are

no longer called.

- ProgrammableScrollAnimator::MainThreadScrollingDidChange() is

merged into UpdateCompositorAnimations() to handle the situation

of running animation switched to main thread.



Original CL description:



Previously PLSA::SetShouldScrollOnMainThread() was called only for

user-scrollable scrollable areas, and missed the case when a

composited composited scrollable area became not user-scrollable

(and not-composited), causing wrong scroll animation running on the

wrong thread.



Now remove PLSA::SetShouldScrollOnMainThread() and let

PLSA::ShouldScrollOnMainThread() always return the correct status.

In most cases the function is not called at all, or just once for

each animating scroller, so the new code actually costs less.
